The former is utilitarian and to my mind necessary and relatively harmless—AirBnB creates an AI assistant whose only function (bias) is the world of vacation home rentals and real estate, etc. The latter brings up all kinds of thoughts—is the proliferation of warring ideological AI biases better or worse than aspiring to some kind of (imagined?impossible?) ideal ‘neutrality’, whereby the AI (a Chatbot for example) has at its disposal all the data to not only collate and ‘mimic’ all possible sides of a topic or argument but also to ultimately synthesizes *its own* subjective conclusion? Simply creating a biased model (from its creator input) feel a bit like a vanity project for amplifying one’s own perspective via a well-trained seal. Not a condemnation of anything, but some distinctions I’m curious to tease out if possible….(cont’d) 👉

…Choice is certainly a component of ‘intelligence’ in that data are scrutinized, ordered, comprehended and finally used to make a decision one way or another. I’m not a comp engineer, or any kind of dev or coder or theoretical maths PhD, but I do come from a background of linguistics, language models, and how meaning is created (including bias) in human intelligence.
